WEBVTT

﻿1
00:00:00.084 --> 00:00:02.545
The school budget.
which Anderson single-handedly oversees.

2
00:00:02.628 --> 00:00:04.964
said we spent $129 on mousepads.

3
00:00:05.047 --> 00:00:06.382
No mousepads.

4
00:00:06.465 --> 00:00:08.008
You know how I feel about protecting Liz.

5
00:00:08.092 --> 00:00:09.260
I apologized.

6
00:00:09.343 --> 00:00:10.553
Previously on Elle...

7
00:00:10.636 --> 00:00:12.179
[Kimberly] Robin's funeral
will be in Denver.

8
00:00:12.263 --> 00:00:14.515
where most of her family lives.
so I panicked

9
00:00:14.598 --> 00:00:16.559
and offered to throw her a memorial.

10
00:00:16.642 --> 00:00:17.685
Let me help.

11
00:00:17.768 --> 00:00:20.521
Whoever Robin was to you...

12
00:00:20.604 --> 00:00:23.357
thank you for being here today
to pay your respects.

13
00:00:24.567 --> 00:00:25.901
I'm so sorry for your loss.

14
00:00:25.985 --> 00:00:27.611
I appreciate that.

15
00:00:27.695 --> 00:00:29.655
-I kissed Elle.
-I don't want to look at you!

16
00:00:29.739 --> 00:00:33.409
I don't want to be around you. and you can
tell Elle I am done with her. too!

17
00:00:33.492 --> 00:00:35.619
I don't want to lose Shannon as a friend.

18
00:00:35.703 --> 00:00:37.705
[pensive music playing]

19
00:00:39.123 --> 00:00:40.833
[sighs]

20
00:00:42.960 --> 00:00:45.880
[slow. gentle music playing]

21
00:00:52.928 --> 00:00:54.221
These are for you.

22
00:00:55.639 --> 00:00:58.225
And these are for your daughter.

23
00:00:58.309 --> 00:01:01.103
who's probably never
going to speak to me again.

24
00:01:02.563 --> 00:01:06.400
I am so. so sorry.

25
00:01:06.484 --> 00:01:08.194
To both of you.

26
00:01:12.406 --> 00:01:14.116
You know. while I have you here.

27
00:01:14.200 --> 00:01:16.285
maybe you could put in
a good word to Shannon.

28
00:01:16.368 --> 00:01:18.120
She's gone. too.

29
00:01:18.204 --> 00:01:20.247
Well. she's not dead. obviously.

30
00:01:20.331 --> 00:01:21.624
Not that there's anything wrong with that.

31
00:01:24.084 --> 00:01:28.506
I'm so sorry I... I kissed Miles.

32
00:01:28.589 --> 00:01:31.467
Your daughter had recently
broken up with him.

33
00:01:31.550 --> 00:01:33.969
She broke up with him.

34
00:01:34.053 --> 00:01:38.349
I don't know if you caught that
before you... you know.

35
00:01:40.059 --> 00:01:41.977
But I will make this right.

36
00:01:42.061 --> 00:01:43.562
[car engine revving]

37
00:01:43.646 --> 00:01:46.398
-[horn blares]
-Hey!

38
00:01:46.482 --> 00:01:49.902
Some of us are busy
paying our respects here.

39
00:01:49.985 --> 00:01:51.362
[sighs]

40
00:01:53.239 --> 00:01:56.408
Why isn't there a stop sign
at this intersection?

41
00:01:56.492 --> 00:01:57.827
[gasps]

42
00:01:57.910 --> 00:02:00.287
Why isn't there a stop sign
at this intersection?

43
00:02:01.372 --> 00:02:03.374
-[indistinct chatter]
-[distant phone ringing]

44
00:02:08.462 --> 00:02:12.466
[bell dinging]

45
00:02:12.550 --> 00:02:14.134
One will suffice.

46
00:02:14.218 --> 00:02:16.846
Hi. I have this petition for a stop sign.

47
00:02:16.929 --> 00:02:20.224
There's this really dangerous intersection
near our school.

48
00:02:20.307 --> 00:02:22.685
You'll see
I have the requisite 1.000 signatures.

49
00:02:24.603 --> 00:02:28.440
So. you're going to win Shannon back
with a stop sign?

50
00:02:28.524 --> 00:02:31.277
Seems like it would've been easier
to just not kiss her boyfriend.

51
00:02:31.360 --> 00:02:35.030
Ex-boyfriend. She means ex-boyfriend.

52
00:02:35.114 --> 00:02:38.868
That detail's not
for public consumption yet.

53
00:02:38.951 --> 00:02:41.662
And this isn't about Shannon and me.
It's for the greater good.

54
00:02:43.163 --> 00:02:47.710
I can't undo the mistake I made.
but this is something I can do.

55
00:02:47.793 --> 00:02:49.378
With your help. of course.

56
00:02:49.461 --> 00:02:50.754
According to our records.

57
00:02:50.838 --> 00:02:55.092
we already approved a stop sign
at the corner of 50th and Evans.

58
00:02:55.175 --> 00:02:57.136
Last June. in fact.

59
00:02:57.219 --> 00:03:01.098
I can assure you. there is
no such stop sign at said intersection.

60
00:03:01.181 --> 00:03:03.183
We approved the stop sign.

61
00:03:03.267 --> 00:03:06.312
but the school elected
to handle contracting themselves.

62
00:03:07.646 --> 00:03:09.690
Sorry. I-I don't understand.

63
00:03:09.773 --> 00:03:13.611
Are you saying someone ordered a stop sign
but never paid for it?

64
00:03:13.694 --> 00:03:15.821
It says right here.

65
00:03:15.905 --> 00:03:17.281
"One stop sign.

66
00:03:17.364 --> 00:03:21.201
requested by and granted
to Rainier West High School board.

67
00:03:21.285 --> 00:03:23.954
point of contact Shane Anderson."

68
00:03:25.039 --> 00:03:26.999
♪ I'm only happy when it rains ♪

69
00:03:27.082 --> 00:03:29.084
[♪ Garbage sings
"I'm Only Happy When It Rains"]

70
00:03:29.168 --> 00:03:33.213
♪ I'm only happy when it's complicated ♪

71
00:03:33.297 --> 00:03:35.215
♪ And though I know you can't ♪

72
00:03:35.299 --> 00:03:37.217
♪ appreciate it ♪

73
00:03:37.301 --> 00:03:40.638
♪ I'm only happy when it rains ♪

74
00:03:41.305 --> 00:03:43.265
♪ Pour your ♪

75
00:03:43.349 --> 00:03:45.768
-♪ misery down ♪
-♪ Pour your misery down ♪

76
00:03:45.851 --> 00:03:47.853
♪ Pour your misery ♪

77
00:03:47.937 --> 00:03:49.271
-♪ down on me ♪
-♪ Pour your misery ♪

78
00:03:49.355 --> 00:03:51.941
-♪ down ♪
-♪ Pour your misery down ♪

79
00:03:52.024 --> 00:03:53.275
♪ Pour ♪

80
00:03:53.359 --> 00:03:57.279
♪ You can keep me company as long as ♪

81
00:03:57.363 --> 00:03:59.323
♪ you don't care ♪

82
00:04:01.367 --> 00:04:04.244
♪ I'm only happy when it rains ♪

83
00:04:05.371 --> 00:04:09.041
♪ You wanna hear about my new obsession? ♪

84
00:04:09.124 --> 00:04:10.626
♪ I'm riding high upon ♪

85
00:04:10.709 --> 00:04:13.087
♪ a deep depression ♪

86
00:04:13.170 --> 00:04:16.048
♪ I'm only happy when it rains ♪

87
00:04:16.131 --> 00:04:19.134
♪ Pour some misery down on me ♪

88
00:04:19.218 --> 00:04:22.054
♪ I'm only happy when it rains ♪

89
00:04:22.137 --> 00:04:24.056
♪ Pour some misery down...

90
00:04:27.393 --> 00:04:29.687
[Elle] Are you following?

91
00:04:29.770 --> 00:04:31.855
[Donna] Can you rewind a little bit?
[sighs]

92
00:04:31.939 --> 00:04:33.482
Some video store humor for you there.

93
00:04:33.565 --> 00:04:35.943
But. also. I mean it. Go back a little.

94
00:04:36.026 --> 00:04:38.070
Sure. Principal Anderson either

95
00:04:38.153 --> 00:04:41.198
forgot to purchase the stop sign
he ordered for the school entrance.

96
00:04:41.281 --> 00:04:44.410
or he got the school board to cough up
the money and took it for himself.

97
00:04:44.493 --> 00:04:47.579
Just like he did with the yield sign and
the two "no parking" signs by the track.

98
00:04:47.663 --> 00:04:49.623
[Elle] Anderson requested and received

99
00:04:49.707 --> 00:04:53.252
$15.600 from the school board
for campus signs alone.

100
00:04:53.335 --> 00:04:55.504
[Dustin] And that doesn't even include
mousepads. tater tots.

101
00:04:55.587 --> 00:04:57.297
gym mats and a bunch of other stuff

102
00:04:57.381 --> 00:04:59.383
we found in the school budget
that doesn't exist in real life.

103
00:04:59.466 --> 00:05:00.592
Mm.

104
00:05:00.676 --> 00:05:02.094
Did you pay for that candy?

105
00:05:02.177 --> 00:05:05.931
As if I'm gonna put Blockbuster
out of business. They'll be fine.

106
00:05:06.015 --> 00:05:08.434
This is what got you fired
in the first place.

107
00:05:08.517 --> 00:05:10.519
All right. I know you're all
very excited by this theory.

108
00:05:10.602 --> 00:05:13.897
but I think you should direct
your amateur detective efforts elsewhere.

109
00:05:13.981 --> 00:05:15.691
[electronic entry bell chimes]

110
00:05:17.192 --> 00:05:18.944
What is he doing here?

111
00:05:19.028 --> 00:05:21.488
Hey. uh. Dustin called me. filled me in.

112
00:05:21.572 --> 00:05:23.824
Why would you do that?

113
00:05:23.907 --> 00:05:26.744
We can use the extra brainpower.

114
00:05:26.827 --> 00:05:28.287
Plus. he's Shannon's boyfriend.

115
00:05:28.370 --> 00:05:29.872
-Ex.
-Ex.

116
00:05:30.831 --> 00:05:32.249
[electronic entry bell chimes]

117
00:05:32.332 --> 00:05:33.417
What am I missing?

118
00:05:33.500 --> 00:05:35.961
[whispering] They're on
a friendship sabbatical.

119
00:05:36.045 --> 00:05:37.755
I'm just here to help.

120
00:05:41.216 --> 00:05:44.887
Anyway. you were Principal Anderson's
secretary for two years.

121
00:05:44.970 --> 00:05:47.139
Do you think
he could've stolen all that money?

122
00:05:47.222 --> 00:05:49.349
I don't know. He's such a rule follower.

123
00:05:49.433 --> 00:05:51.143
-[Dustin chuckles]
-[clears throat] Well.

124
00:05:51.226 --> 00:05:54.313
the teachers love him. parents love him.

125
00:05:54.396 --> 00:05:57.316
He was just a finalist
for State Principal of the Year.

126
00:05:57.399 --> 00:05:58.400
The people spoke.

127
00:05:58.484 --> 00:06:01.236
But... but he sucks.

128
00:06:01.320 --> 00:06:05.741
Fine. but you can't just order things
and not buy them.

129
00:06:05.824 --> 00:06:08.368
There is a record.
And. plus. I would know.

130
00:06:08.452 --> 00:06:11.580
I've spent hours
filing receipts and invoices.

131
00:06:11.663 --> 00:06:13.123
[Dustin] Did he have receipts
for the stuff we don't have?

132
00:06:13.207 --> 00:06:15.125
Mousepads? Tater tots? Gym mats?

133
00:06:15.209 --> 00:06:17.878
I don't know...
'cause I'm staying out of it.

134
00:06:17.961 --> 00:06:20.380
Hypothetically.
where would these receipts be?

135
00:06:20.464 --> 00:06:23.842
In his file cabinet in his office.
which is always locked.

136
00:06:23.926 --> 00:06:26.053
-Can we break in?
-[Dustin] If it opens.

137
00:06:26.136 --> 00:06:27.846
-it can be broken into.
-How?

138
00:06:27.930 --> 00:06:32.893
[gasps] I have a lot of bobby pins
from my French-twist period.

139
00:06:33.977 --> 00:06:35.729
-We steal Frank's master key.
-Got it.

140
00:06:35.813 --> 00:06:38.023
Wait. Frank the maintenance guy?
I thought he was fired.

141
00:06:38.107 --> 00:06:41.026
His schedule got shifted to weekends.
Budget cuts.

142
00:06:41.110 --> 00:06:44.238
[Donna] Yeah. good luck. When I'd ask
Frank for the key to the snack closet.

143
00:06:44.321 --> 00:06:46.115
-he'd say. "From my cold. dead hands."
-[Liz] Right.

144
00:06:46.198 --> 00:06:48.742
-because you have to pay for snacks.
-[moans]

145
00:06:48.826 --> 00:06:50.452
-They're-- Okay.
-[Elle] Okay. so let's say

146
00:06:50.536 --> 00:06:53.664
we somehow get into the school
on Saturday. get the key off Frank.

147
00:06:53.747 --> 00:06:55.749
-What do we do?
-We break into Anderson's office.

148
00:06:55.833 --> 00:06:59.628
make copies of the receipts.
cross-reference them with the budget.

149
00:06:59.711 --> 00:07:02.047
If anything's missing. that's evidence
we can take to the school board.

150
00:07:02.131 --> 00:07:05.801
Easy. Now we just need an excuse
to be in school over the weekend.

151
00:07:08.846 --> 00:07:10.514
Guys?

152
00:07:10.597 --> 00:07:12.349
[adventurous music playing]

153
00:07:19.064 --> 00:07:20.274
[microphone feedback humming]

154
00:07:20.357 --> 00:07:21.817
[Liz] Hello. Rainier West High.

155
00:07:21.900 --> 00:07:24.903
This is Liz Miller coming to you live
from the AV room.

156
00:07:24.987 --> 00:07:26.613
Please rise for the national anthem.

157
00:07:26.697 --> 00:07:28.740
[♪ Bikini Kill sings "Rebel Girl"]

158
00:07:33.871 --> 00:07:35.247
♪ That girl thinks ♪

159
00:07:35.330 --> 00:07:37.457
♪ she's the queen of the neighborhood ♪

160
00:07:37.541 --> 00:07:40.669
-Coming through.
-♪ She's got the hottest trike in town ♪

161
00:07:40.752 --> 00:07:41.920
♪ That girl...

162
00:07:42.004 --> 00:07:43.755
Dustin. principal's office. now.

163
00:07:43.839 --> 00:07:45.132
♪ so high ♪

164
00:07:45.215 --> 00:07:46.466
♪ I think I wanna be...

165
00:07:46.550 --> 00:07:50.345
This period was not designed
for you to take a nap.

166
00:07:50.429 --> 00:07:52.055
♪ Rebel girl ♪

167
00:07:52.139 --> 00:07:53.724
♪ Rebel girl. you are the queen of...

168
00:07:53.807 --> 00:07:55.559
Take that to the principal's office.

169
00:07:55.642 --> 00:07:58.604
♪ Rebel girl. rebel girl ♪

170
00:07:58.687 --> 00:08:03.066
♪ I think I want to take you home.
I want to try on your clothes. uh ♪♪

171
00:08:05.068 --> 00:08:06.486
-[record scratches]
-[song stops abruptly]

172
00:08:11.742 --> 00:08:13.035
For you.

173
00:08:17.206 --> 00:08:19.875
From the League of Women Voters.

174
00:08:20.876 --> 00:08:22.127
Huh.

175
00:08:23.420 --> 00:08:24.630
Thank you.

176
00:08:25.839 --> 00:08:26.965
[softly] Thank you.

177
00:08:28.967 --> 00:08:30.802
[woman over P.A.] ...head to
the nurse's office.

178
00:08:32.262 --> 00:08:34.848
-[birds chirping]
-[crow caws]

179
00:08:34.932 --> 00:08:37.142
-[paper rustles]
-[Elle] Listen up.

180
00:08:37.226 --> 00:08:40.229
"Operation: Manifest Anderson's Demise

181
00:08:40.312 --> 00:08:45.317
by Breaking into His Office
to Expose His Hypocrisy" starts now.

182
00:08:45.400 --> 00:08:46.526
Subtle.

183
00:08:46.610 --> 00:08:48.528
[Elle] Once the detention monitor
gets here.

184
00:08:48.612 --> 00:08:52.032
we'll initiate Phase One:
key loop sabotage.

185
00:08:52.115 --> 00:08:55.160
I took the liberty
of fleshing out the plan a bit.

186
00:08:55.244 --> 00:08:56.411
[Dustin] What's that smell?

187
00:08:58.747 --> 00:08:59.748
[Liz sniffs]

188
00:08:59.831 --> 00:09:02.501
-Is this... lavender scented?
-[Dustin sniffs]

189
00:09:02.584 --> 00:09:04.962
Great nose. Liz.

190
00:09:05.045 --> 00:09:09.549
Lavender is a naturally calming fragrance.
and heists are known to be quite nervy.

191
00:09:10.759 --> 00:09:14.179
Whoa. When did detention get so uncool?

192
00:09:14.263 --> 00:09:15.722
I'm sorry. what are you doing here?

193
00:09:15.806 --> 00:09:19.726
Oh. turns out
nine tardies is six too many. so...

194
00:09:20.394 --> 00:09:24.147
[scoffs] Didn't expect to see
Good Girl Barbie serving time.

195
00:09:24.231 --> 00:09:27.818
What'd you do? Turn in an English essay
in the dialect of a Valley girl?

196
00:09:28.402 --> 00:09:30.445
I don't speak Valley.

197
00:09:30.529 --> 00:09:33.115
I only go there for sushi
and designer discounts.

198
00:09:33.198 --> 00:09:35.200
-Oh.
-[Liz] Yeah. Elle's actually

199
00:09:35.284 --> 00:09:37.828
-the biggest badass here.
-[scoffs] Really?

200
00:09:37.911 --> 00:09:39.079
Enlighten me.

201
00:09:40.497 --> 00:09:43.792
Pie to Anderson in the face.
Don't want to talk about it.

202
00:09:43.875 --> 00:09:45.877
Elle Woods pied the principal.

203
00:09:45.961 --> 00:09:48.714
That's... shockingly epic.

204
00:09:49.464 --> 00:09:50.549
Thank you.

205
00:09:50.632 --> 00:09:54.428
But it's now 9:23 a.m.

206
00:09:54.511 --> 00:09:56.346
Does detention not start at 9:15?

207
00:09:56.430 --> 00:09:58.890
-Where's our monitor?
-[footsteps approaching]

208
00:09:58.974 --> 00:10:00.183
Oh. here we go.

209
00:10:01.184 --> 00:10:02.436
I heard that.

210
00:10:03.770 --> 00:10:06.231
-You forgot your lunch.
-Oh. I didn't--

211
00:10:09.026 --> 00:10:12.571
I think someone might miss
being at school.

212
00:10:12.654 --> 00:10:16.700
[Martindale] Okay. delinquents.
here's how this is gonna work.

213
00:10:16.783 --> 00:10:20.746
Every one of these books is
gonna be reshelved by 3:00 p.m..

214
00:10:20.829 --> 00:10:24.249
so get friendly
with our Dewey decimal system.

215
00:10:28.337 --> 00:10:29.880
[feedback hums]

216
00:10:29.963 --> 00:10:31.673
[sighs]

217
00:10:33.633 --> 00:10:34.676
[whispers] Phase One.

218
00:10:34.760 --> 00:10:36.762
[intriguing music playing]

219
00:10:41.975 --> 00:10:46.646
[clearing throat]

220
00:10:46.730 --> 00:10:48.732
[clearing throat loudly]

221
00:10:50.233 --> 00:10:52.444
May I please request the hall pass?

222
00:10:57.991 --> 00:11:00.118
[grunting softly]

223
00:11:07.292 --> 00:11:08.919
[gasps. whispers] Frank.

224
00:11:11.671 --> 00:11:13.090
[gasps]

225
00:11:15.717 --> 00:11:17.427
[groans]

226
00:11:20.389 --> 00:11:21.932
[groans]

227
00:11:24.935 --> 00:11:26.937
♪ ♪

228
00:11:28.000 --> 00:11:34.074
Watch Online Movies and Series for FREE
www.osdb.link/lm

229
00:11:39.825 --> 00:11:41.743
[clattering outside room]

230
00:11:47.791 --> 00:11:49.543
Elle should be back by now.

231
00:11:51.503 --> 00:11:53.255
"9:15. cut key loop.

232
00:11:53.338 --> 00:11:54.923
10:15. flood toilets."

233
00:11:55.006 --> 00:11:57.717
What is this
and why does it smell like my grandma?

234
00:11:57.801 --> 00:11:59.219
Not for you.

235
00:12:02.722 --> 00:12:06.810
Okay. you guys are being even more...
yourselves than usual.

236
00:12:06.893 --> 00:12:09.938
Did you Trojan horse yourselves
into detention? What's going on?

237
00:12:10.021 --> 00:12:11.148
Okay. why don't you go stack some books.

238
00:12:11.231 --> 00:12:13.733
I should know if I'm about to become
an unwitting accomplice

239
00:12:13.817 --> 00:12:15.527
to some lame secret operation.

240
00:12:16.570 --> 00:12:20.323
Guys. uh. she could actually be useful.

241
00:12:20.407 --> 00:12:21.533
-Oh. Thank you.
-Oh. why?

242
00:12:21.616 --> 00:12:23.410
Do we have a role
for an overly confident mean girl?

243
00:12:23.493 --> 00:12:26.538
Mrs. Martindale. I think my fellow
delinquents are up to something shady.

244
00:12:26.621 --> 00:12:28.290
Okay. you have no idea what you're doing.

245
00:12:28.373 --> 00:12:31.793
As I said moments ago.
I would love to be in the loop.

246
00:12:35.172 --> 00:12:38.925
Fine. We think someone here.
at a very high level.

247
00:12:39.009 --> 00:12:41.761
is embezzling money from the school.

248
00:12:43.430 --> 00:12:49.269
So you all wasted the only sunny Saturday
in the last two months to. what. care?

249
00:12:49.352 --> 00:12:50.937
You're right. super useful.

250
00:12:51.021 --> 00:12:53.064
Okay. I'm sorry. It's not like
it's our own personal money.

251
00:12:53.148 --> 00:12:54.858
The stolen funds
were meant for a stop sign

252
00:12:54.941 --> 00:12:56.693
in the intersection
where Robin had her accident.

253
00:13:00.489 --> 00:13:02.616
Count me in. Who do I bludgeon?

254
00:13:02.699 --> 00:13:06.369
Anderson. [sighs] We need
to break into his office to prove it.

255
00:13:08.538 --> 00:13:10.665
[intriguing music playing]

256
00:13:19.674 --> 00:13:21.718
What the...?

257
00:13:21.801 --> 00:13:22.844
Great.

258
00:13:34.272 --> 00:13:35.607
[door opens]

259
00:13:38.151 --> 00:13:39.778
Elle.

260
00:13:39.861 --> 00:13:42.322
Ms. Burke. Hi!

261
00:13:42.405 --> 00:13:43.490
Hi.

262
00:13:43.573 --> 00:13:47.536
Oh. I'm just coming from the bathroom.

263
00:13:47.619 --> 00:13:49.788
You know. taking the scenic route.

264
00:13:49.871 --> 00:13:51.998
Got to keep the blood flowing. right?

265
00:13:52.082 --> 00:13:55.085
Detention's the enemy
of cardiovascular health.

266
00:13:55.168 --> 00:13:56.628
Detention?

267
00:13:56.711 --> 00:13:59.089
Doesn't sound like Elle Woods.

268
00:14:00.382 --> 00:14:03.718
If anyone asks.
I threw a pie in Anderson's face.

269
00:14:03.802 --> 00:14:05.762
[chuckles] Wha... [clears throat] What?

270
00:14:05.845 --> 00:14:08.431
I didn't actually.
but all my friends got detention.

271
00:14:08.515 --> 00:14:12.394
so I decided to join them
for moral support.

272
00:14:12.477 --> 00:14:15.772
Oh. Protective and caring.

273
00:14:15.855 --> 00:14:17.607
How very Cancer of you.

274
00:14:17.691 --> 00:14:19.442
Oh. I'm a Gemini.

275
00:14:19.526 --> 00:14:21.945
Oh. Maybe cusp. then.

276
00:14:22.028 --> 00:14:24.030
No. My birthday is June 20th.

277
00:14:24.114 --> 00:14:25.574
Purebred Gemini.

278
00:14:25.657 --> 00:14:27.492
My-my sister is Gemini rising.

279
00:14:28.493 --> 00:14:29.995
Or Gemini moon?

280
00:14:30.078 --> 00:14:31.746
Or she dated a Gemini?

281
00:14:31.830 --> 00:14:33.373
Wow. I have got to call my sister.
[chuckles]

282
00:14:33.456 --> 00:14:35.750
-[chuckles]
-Sorry. Uh. you should...

283
00:14:35.834 --> 00:14:37.711
-you should get back to detention.
-Yes.

284
00:14:37.794 --> 00:14:40.255
Oh. well. there is something
I never thought I'd say to you.

285
00:14:40.338 --> 00:14:42.507
-You and me both.
-[chuckles] Oh.

286
00:14:42.591 --> 00:14:43.800
Don't forget to sign up
for the Science Fair!

287
00:14:43.883 --> 00:14:45.260
Got it.

288
00:14:46.052 --> 00:14:48.513
[Dean] Welcome to Medina Town Hall.

289
00:14:48.597 --> 00:14:51.141
Like any other hall in any other town.

290
00:14:51.224 --> 00:14:53.560
You brought me here to do... what?

291
00:14:53.643 --> 00:14:57.897
[Dean] Well. when we first met.
you were very...

292
00:14:57.981 --> 00:15:00.066
honest about my campaign
needing a refresh.

293
00:15:00.150 --> 00:15:02.360
But I don't know anything
about political speeches.

294
00:15:02.444 --> 00:15:04.112
You know about presentation.

295
00:15:05.196 --> 00:15:07.574
All right? If it wasn't for you.
I would still have that mustache

296
00:15:07.657 --> 00:15:09.701
that nobody else told me
made me look like a serial killer.

297
00:15:09.784 --> 00:15:10.869
Ooh.

298
00:15:10.952 --> 00:15:13.788
And I would still be dressing like. um...

299
00:15:13.872 --> 00:15:14.873
Ted Bundy.

300
00:15:14.956 --> 00:15:17.834
[chuckles] I was gonna say
Jordan Catalano. but...

301
00:15:17.917 --> 00:15:21.755
From My So-Called Life? No.

302
00:15:21.838 --> 00:15:24.341
Here's my question.

303
00:15:24.424 --> 00:15:26.051
How do I get people to like me?

304
00:15:29.346 --> 00:15:31.556
[sighs]

305
00:15:31.640 --> 00:15:32.932
You'll be presenting here?

306
00:15:33.016 --> 00:15:35.393
-Mm-hmm.
-And against that color scheme?

307
00:15:36.353 --> 00:15:37.771
You're gonna be standing?

308
00:15:39.939 --> 00:15:42.692
All right. get up there.
Let's see how the people will see you.

309
00:15:42.776 --> 00:15:44.319
[Dean] Okay.

310
00:15:49.616 --> 00:15:51.993
Yikes.

311
00:15:52.077 --> 00:15:53.578
That's what I'm talking about.

312
00:15:53.662 --> 00:15:55.080
-Nixon.
-Oh.

313
00:15:55.163 --> 00:15:56.623
He sweat through his first debate
with Kennedy.

314
00:15:56.706 --> 00:15:59.042
-It cost him the entire election.
-Okay.

315
00:16:00.126 --> 00:16:02.754
We're gonna need some powder foundation.

316
00:16:02.837 --> 00:16:04.589
some incandescent lighting.

317
00:16:04.673 --> 00:16:09.552
and I will send you to my chiropractor
to work on your posture a bit.

318
00:16:09.636 --> 00:16:11.012
And I know you've been kind of

319
00:16:11.096 --> 00:16:15.600
experimenting with a few things up there.
but I'm just gonna fly out my hairstylist.

320
00:16:15.684 --> 00:16:18.269
Great. [laughs]

321
00:16:18.353 --> 00:16:21.773
Cool. You want to come check out
my campaign office after this?

322
00:16:21.856 --> 00:16:25.860
Oh. I would love to. but I got to
pick Elle up from detention at 3:00.

323
00:16:25.944 --> 00:16:27.404
Detention?

324
00:16:27.487 --> 00:16:29.656
She seemed so sweet
when she was cajoling me

325
00:16:29.739 --> 00:16:31.574
into renting a booth for her homecoming.

326
00:16:31.658 --> 00:16:34.703
Yeah. she has some ludicrous theory

327
00:16:34.786 --> 00:16:37.664
about her principal stealing funds
from the school.

328
00:16:37.747 --> 00:16:39.999
Can you go to the other podium?

329
00:16:40.083 --> 00:16:43.420
Your better angle
needs to face the TV cameras.

330
00:16:43.503 --> 00:16:44.629
Hold on.

331
00:16:44.713 --> 00:16:47.382
E-Elle thinks that Shane Anderson
is stealing money?

332
00:16:47.465 --> 00:16:52.137
Yes. And she can be very convincing
when she's invested in something.

333
00:16:53.638 --> 00:16:54.639
[smacks lips]

334
00:16:54.723 --> 00:16:58.309
I think our best bet is
to do this by candlelight.

335
00:16:58.393 --> 00:17:00.687
-[door opens]
-[footsteps approaching]

336
00:17:07.152 --> 00:17:08.528
Phase One is complete.

337
00:17:08.611 --> 00:17:10.196
Is Phase Two killing Anderson?

338
00:17:11.406 --> 00:17:13.199
-You guys told Kimberly?
-I was forced.

339
00:17:13.283 --> 00:17:14.868
[Kimberly] Oh. like someone forced you

340
00:17:14.951 --> 00:17:16.703
-to wear those pants?
-Remember when you got nicer?

341
00:17:16.786 --> 00:17:17.871
Can we go back to that?

342
00:17:17.954 --> 00:17:19.706
Okay. Phase Two.

343
00:17:19.789 --> 00:17:23.668
What does "Consolidate and secure
personal care essentials" mean?

344
00:17:25.253 --> 00:17:26.713
[smacks lips]

345
00:17:26.796 --> 00:17:28.798
[whimsical music playing]

346
00:17:40.351 --> 00:17:41.436
Can I help you?

347
00:17:41.519 --> 00:17:44.439
That looks so familiar.

348
00:17:45.148 --> 00:17:48.485
Oh. yeah. it's Cujo.
I kind of thought was banned.

349
00:17:48.568 --> 00:17:51.654
and I will therefore be

350
00:17:51.738 --> 00:17:55.533
prominently placing it right...

351
00:17:55.617 --> 00:17:56.993
here.

352
00:17:57.076 --> 00:17:59.204
No. Your bracelet.

353
00:17:59.287 --> 00:18:01.331
Camp Saddle Rock.

354
00:18:01.414 --> 00:18:05.418
I saw it earlier and thought.
"Who have I seen wearing that before?"

355
00:18:05.502 --> 00:18:10.048
And then I thought.
"Wait. Liz has that bracelet."

356
00:18:10.131 --> 00:18:12.175
-And then I thought--
-Get there faster.

357
00:18:13.468 --> 00:18:15.720
Were you two at camp at the same time?

358
00:18:15.804 --> 00:18:17.889
Why in the world would that matter?

359
00:18:17.972 --> 00:18:21.267
I'm just trying to figure out
what your damage is with each other.

360
00:18:21.351 --> 00:18:22.769
With you and me...

361
00:18:24.562 --> 00:18:26.606
-We don't need to recap.
-Mm.

362
00:18:26.689 --> 00:18:28.817
But Liz is. like.
the most neutral force ever.

363
00:18:28.900 --> 00:18:30.902
[scoffs] I'm sorry.
but Liz is not neutral.

364
00:18:30.985 --> 00:18:33.363
Okay. so something did happen.

365
00:18:33.446 --> 00:18:34.656
Did you have a big fight?

366
00:18:34.739 --> 00:18:36.366
You know. this might shock you.

367
00:18:36.449 --> 00:18:39.619
but our lives didn't just start
the second you appeared at this school.

368
00:18:48.920 --> 00:18:51.422
[sighs] What the hell is
a friendship sabbatical?

369
00:18:51.506 --> 00:18:52.882
What?

370
00:18:52.966 --> 00:18:55.093
You and the running man are being weird.

371
00:18:55.176 --> 00:18:58.012
[chuckling] What? No. we're not.

372
00:18:58.096 --> 00:18:59.222
[Martindale] Stop playing with fire!

373
00:18:59.305 --> 00:19:00.932
I'm not! Everyone's fine!

374
00:19:01.015 --> 00:19:02.600
You'll burn the place down.

375
00:19:05.687 --> 00:19:08.857
Why are the quiet ones always pyromaniacs?

376
00:19:08.940 --> 00:19:11.025
And isn't Cujo banned?

377
00:19:13.403 --> 00:19:14.696
I'm moving to self-help.

378
00:19:19.617 --> 00:19:21.703
[adventurous music playing]

379
00:19:30.837 --> 00:19:34.883
So. uh. I hear you and I are
on some sort of embargo.

380
00:19:36.092 --> 00:19:38.094
Embargo. sabbatical.

381
00:19:38.177 --> 00:19:40.680
Where are we. a thesaurus convention?

382
00:19:44.976 --> 00:19:46.394
Are you okay?

383
00:19:46.477 --> 00:19:47.770
Yep.

384
00:19:47.854 --> 00:19:50.398
You just shelved R. L. Stine in self-help.

385
00:19:51.691 --> 00:19:55.528
[chuckles softly] One could argue
his entire repertoire is a metaphor

386
00:19:55.612 --> 00:19:58.406
for the horrors of teen adolescence.

387
00:19:58.489 --> 00:19:59.616
One could.

388
00:20:02.785 --> 00:20:04.245
I messed up.

389
00:20:05.663 --> 00:20:07.832
Maybe I shouldn't have told Shannon.

390
00:20:08.833 --> 00:20:11.085
You were tiki drunk at her mom's memorial.

391
00:20:11.169 --> 00:20:13.212
I know. I-I screwed up.

392
00:20:14.505 --> 00:20:16.591
But we both tried calling her.

393
00:20:16.674 --> 00:20:18.092
She doesn't want to talk to us.

394
00:20:19.093 --> 00:20:20.637
I'm not sure what else we can do.

395
00:20:20.720 --> 00:20:22.597
Nothing. We do nothing.

396
00:20:22.680 --> 00:20:24.933
No more extended eye contact.

397
00:20:25.016 --> 00:20:27.143
no more leaning against lockers.

398
00:20:27.226 --> 00:20:28.770
-no more--
-No speaking to each other?

399
00:20:28.853 --> 00:20:31.898
I think we should avoid
anything involving mouths.

400
00:20:34.734 --> 00:20:36.444
Okay.

401
00:20:36.527 --> 00:20:40.406
Can I ask. respectfully. why?

402
00:20:41.866 --> 00:20:43.743
I mean. she already knows.

403
00:20:43.826 --> 00:20:45.244
She's not here.

404
00:20:48.247 --> 00:20:50.333
Because it's just not me. Miles.

405
00:20:51.334 --> 00:20:53.002
I'm not that kind of girl.

406
00:21:00.677 --> 00:21:03.972
Uh. there's a plumbing emergency
in the ladies' room.

407
00:21:04.055 --> 00:21:06.432
What? Did you say something?

408
00:21:06.516 --> 00:21:08.893
Toilet... [blows raspberry]

409
00:21:08.977 --> 00:21:10.520
...exploded.

410
00:21:10.603 --> 00:21:13.147
[sighs] I'll call Frank.

411
00:21:13.231 --> 00:21:15.233
[intriguing music playing]

412
00:21:18.486 --> 00:21:19.737
That's my cue.

413
00:21:20.738 --> 00:21:22.156
Good luck.

414
00:21:27.495 --> 00:21:29.247
[liquid sloshing]

415
00:21:29.330 --> 00:21:31.165
[sighs]

416
00:21:31.249 --> 00:21:33.042
Aw. come on.

417
00:21:41.884 --> 00:21:43.886
[suspenseful music playing]

418
00:21:47.515 --> 00:21:49.600
Come on. come on. come on.

419
00:21:50.601 --> 00:21:52.478
Why does every key look the same?

420
00:21:52.562 --> 00:21:53.896
[Anderson] Miles?

421
00:21:56.274 --> 00:21:57.442
Principal Anderson.

422
00:22:04.032 --> 00:22:05.700
[Kimberly] Hey.

423
00:22:05.783 --> 00:22:07.368
Did you drop this?

424
00:22:07.452 --> 00:22:09.203
-Hilarious.
-I thought so.

425
00:22:09.287 --> 00:22:10.788
Yeah. do you come up with these
ahead of time.

426
00:22:10.872 --> 00:22:12.832
or is this just. like.
off the top of your head?

427
00:22:12.915 --> 00:22:15.001
-Oh. you think I'm funny?
-[Elle] Here's an idea.

428
00:22:15.084 --> 00:22:17.628
Why don't you two stop fighting about...

429
00:22:18.463 --> 00:22:20.465
...the mineral economy.

430
00:22:20.548 --> 00:22:22.050
and start getting ready
for our next phase.

431
00:22:22.133 --> 00:22:23.134
[Miles] Hey. guys.

432
00:22:24.302 --> 00:22:25.428
We're screwed.

433
00:22:25.511 --> 00:22:28.014
Sixty-one tampons!

434
00:22:28.598 --> 00:22:30.600
And that's not to mention the super pluses

435
00:22:30.683 --> 00:22:35.271
that got so engorged they became
one monster. uh. tampon rat king.

436
00:22:37.273 --> 00:22:39.901
-Yep. we're screwed.
-Fire. blood or flood.

437
00:22:39.984 --> 00:22:43.863
I am not to be bothered on my days off
unless there is a fire. blood or flood.

438
00:22:43.946 --> 00:22:46.365
and you all chose the latter.

439
00:22:47.075 --> 00:22:50.119
Mrs. Martindale.
you may take the rest of the day off.

440
00:22:53.498 --> 00:22:54.749
Uh... [clears throat]

441
00:22:54.832 --> 00:22:56.292
-They're all accounted for.
-Mm.

442
00:22:56.375 --> 00:22:57.794
[Martindale] The one
in the hoodie's alive.

443
00:22:57.877 --> 00:22:59.670
He just looks comatose.

444
00:23:03.925 --> 00:23:05.134
[sighs]

445
00:23:06.344 --> 00:23:07.595
Uh. Miss Woods?

446
00:23:07.678 --> 00:23:10.098
Yeah. might I ask what you're doing here?

447
00:23:17.980 --> 00:23:21.067
I am here to serve my time
just like everyone else.

448
00:23:21.150 --> 00:23:23.444
Uh-huh. Well. I'm just looking
at my roster here.

449
00:23:23.528 --> 00:23:26.447
I got the athlete. the basket case.
the princess.

450
00:23:26.531 --> 00:23:28.825
the criminal. but no Elle Woods. so...

451
00:23:28.908 --> 00:23:30.743
what are you doing here. Miss Woods?

452
00:23:30.827 --> 00:23:32.870
[tense music playing]

453
00:23:32.954 --> 00:23:35.164
[laughs softly] You remember.

454
00:23:35.248 --> 00:23:37.208
[mumbles] When I pied you in the face.

455
00:23:39.210 --> 00:23:41.462
When you... I'm sorry. when you what?

456
00:23:41.546 --> 00:23:43.381
You know.

457
00:23:43.464 --> 00:23:45.133
[singsong] When I pied you in the face.

458
00:23:45.216 --> 00:23:48.219
I... no. I don't understand
anything you're saying.

459
00:23:48.302 --> 00:23:50.680
When she pied you in the face.

460
00:23:50.763 --> 00:23:52.390
[stammers] Oh.

461
00:23:52.473 --> 00:23:53.891
[stammers]

462
00:23:53.975 --> 00:23:58.521
You mean the lemon meringue you gifted me
for some woman thing?

463
00:23:58.604 --> 00:24:00.022
-Wha--
-What?

464
00:24:02.275 --> 00:24:04.193
Seriously! Why are you here?

465
00:24:09.532 --> 00:24:11.117
To scare myself straight.

466
00:24:11.200 --> 00:24:15.121
Well. I guess now you're here
because you lied.

467
00:24:15.204 --> 00:24:16.664
-[clipboard clatters]
-New deal.

468
00:24:16.747 --> 00:24:19.333
No more hall passes.

469
00:24:19.417 --> 00:24:24.088
We are all staying put until 3:00.

470
00:24:24.172 --> 00:24:26.174
[Dustin] What if we need
to use the facilities?

471
00:24:26.257 --> 00:24:28.509
Then I guess you're gonna
have to get familiar

472
00:24:28.593 --> 00:24:31.179
with the concept of holding it.

473
00:24:32.471 --> 00:24:33.681
[soft groan]

474
00:24:36.684 --> 00:24:39.896
Oh. my God. You're Ally Sheedy.

475
00:24:41.272 --> 00:24:43.107
-[whispers] Elle Woods.
-No. in The Breakfast Club.

476
00:24:43.191 --> 00:24:44.984
there's the whole thing
where they learn that Ally Sheedy

477
00:24:45.067 --> 00:24:48.237
didn't even have to be in detention.
she just showed up.

478
00:24:50.907 --> 00:24:52.533
-Okay. I couldn't do it.
-[groans]

479
00:24:52.617 --> 00:24:53.951
-I really tried.
-[sighs] Mm-hmm.

480
00:24:54.035 --> 00:24:56.329
I even went to his office with the pie.

481
00:24:56.412 --> 00:24:58.956
But I'm not a natural rule breaker.

482
00:24:59.040 --> 00:25:01.626
and the consequences
really flash before your eyes

483
00:25:01.709 --> 00:25:03.211
once you're face-to-face with them.

484
00:25:04.170 --> 00:25:06.214
Can you imagine
what it's like inside her head?

485
00:25:06.297 --> 00:25:07.715
[Liz] Wait. I'm sorry.
I thought that I was Ally Sheedy.

486
00:25:07.798 --> 00:25:10.301
and I thought
that you were Molly Ringwald.

487
00:25:11.302 --> 00:25:12.428
Am I Molly Ringwald?

488
00:25:12.511 --> 00:25:13.804
[Dustin] Maybe we should have

489
00:25:13.888 --> 00:25:15.723
seen it coming
that Elle's bad at being bad.

490
00:25:15.806 --> 00:25:17.308
[Miles] Guys. whatever.

491
00:25:17.391 --> 00:25:19.018
Elle's a model citizen. We knew this.

492
00:25:19.101 --> 00:25:20.728
We have more important things
to deal with right now.

493
00:25:20.811 --> 00:25:22.271
We need a plan B.

494
00:25:28.903 --> 00:25:30.446
[sighs]

495
00:25:30.529 --> 00:25:31.948
[intriguing music playing]

496
00:25:45.211 --> 00:25:47.713
-Yo. Kyle.
-Mm-hmm? Mm-hmm?

497
00:25:47.797 --> 00:25:49.632
Wake up.

498
00:25:49.715 --> 00:25:51.801
You wouldn't happen to have your. uh...

499
00:25:51.884 --> 00:25:54.053
you-know-what. would you?

500
00:25:54.136 --> 00:25:55.805
[whispers] Have his what?

501
00:25:57.848 --> 00:25:59.183
[scoffs]

502
00:25:59.267 --> 00:26:01.852
♪ ♪

503
00:26:01.936 --> 00:26:03.437
[chittering]

504
00:26:03.521 --> 00:26:05.940
All right. Mr. Chuckles.
I'll see you soon.

505
00:26:09.443 --> 00:26:10.611
[Liz] Principal Anderson.

506
00:26:10.695 --> 00:26:13.239
we need you to settle an argument for us.

507
00:26:13.322 --> 00:26:16.117
Do I actually need a pregnancy test
to know that I'm pregnant?

508
00:26:17.368 --> 00:26:19.578
-Uh...
-[Elle] I vote yes.

509
00:26:19.662 --> 00:26:21.914
And I feel like those tests
are just the patriarchy

510
00:26:21.998 --> 00:26:23.874
trying to normalize corporations
charging women money for something

511
00:26:23.958 --> 00:26:25.293
they already know about their own bodies.

512
00:26:25.376 --> 00:26:26.711
[Elle] Hmm. good point.

513
00:26:26.794 --> 00:26:27.920
I do know when I'm ovulating.

514
00:26:28.004 --> 00:26:28.838
-[Liz] Mm-hmm.
-Boo.

515
00:26:28.921 --> 00:26:30.006
Thoughts?

516
00:26:30.089 --> 00:26:31.173
Um...

517
00:26:31.257 --> 00:26:33.718
Well. have you talked
to your parents about this?

518
00:26:33.801 --> 00:26:36.262
Oh. my parents are religious.

519
00:26:36.345 --> 00:26:37.763
We can't talk about sex.

520
00:26:39.724 --> 00:26:42.351
Yeah. um. see Mrs. Nelson

521
00:26:42.435 --> 00:26:44.270
in the guidance counselor's office
next week.

522
00:26:44.353 --> 00:26:46.022
I'm sure she has a pamphlet.

523
00:26:46.105 --> 00:26:47.732
Yeah. or something like that.

524
00:26:50.026 --> 00:26:51.027
Okay.

525
00:26:51.110 --> 00:26:52.611
[faint chittering and scurrying]

526
00:26:52.695 --> 00:26:54.405
-Hmm.
-[Elle] I felt a kick.

527
00:26:54.488 --> 00:26:56.657
[Kimberly] Oh. Oh.

528
00:26:56.741 --> 00:26:57.950
Is that a contraction?

529
00:26:58.034 --> 00:26:59.869
Yeah. I think that's what those feel like.

530
00:26:59.952 --> 00:27:01.370
-Like. it itches. right?
-[grunts]

531
00:27:01.454 --> 00:27:02.788
Uh...

532
00:27:02.872 --> 00:27:04.582
[faint chittering and scurrying]

533
00:27:04.665 --> 00:27:06.125
Does anyone hear that?

534
00:27:06.208 --> 00:27:07.376
Hear what?

535
00:27:07.460 --> 00:27:09.295
[Dustin] I think it's coming
from the ceiling.

536
00:27:09.378 --> 00:27:10.921
Oh. my God. is that a rat?

537
00:27:11.005 --> 00:27:12.298
[sighs]

538
00:27:12.381 --> 00:27:14.008
[Elle] What? A rat?

539
00:27:14.091 --> 00:27:15.843
Yeah. you don't hear
those little toenails?

540
00:27:15.926 --> 00:27:17.720
-[Dustin] We should call maintenance.
-[grunts]

541
00:27:17.803 --> 00:27:19.972
No. no. no. no. no. No. no. no.

542
00:27:21.057 --> 00:27:23.142
This can wait until Monday.

543
00:27:23.225 --> 00:27:24.352
-[metal thumping]
-Oh.

544
00:27:24.435 --> 00:27:25.644
[gasps]

545
00:27:26.729 --> 00:27:28.189
[chittering and scurrying]

546
00:27:29.690 --> 00:27:31.359
-[metal thumps]
-[gasps]

547
00:27:31.442 --> 00:27:32.735
Oh.

548
00:27:34.528 --> 00:27:35.863
-[Liz] Yikes.
-[Elle] Principal Anderson.

549
00:27:35.946 --> 00:27:38.949
if there is a rat trapped
in our school air ducts.

550
00:27:39.033 --> 00:27:42.787
we-- as the most evolved species
of mammal in this room--

551
00:27:42.870 --> 00:27:44.622
are responsible for its well-being.

552
00:27:44.705 --> 00:27:46.082
-Mm-hmm.
-It's a rat.

553
00:27:46.165 --> 00:27:49.168
A rat without access to food or water.

554
00:27:49.251 --> 00:27:50.753
not to mention daylight.

555
00:27:50.836 --> 00:27:53.381
When was the last time
these vents were cleaned?

556
00:27:53.464 --> 00:27:54.507
Anyone?

557
00:27:54.590 --> 00:27:56.967
I genuinely have no idea.

558
00:27:57.051 --> 00:27:59.804
Do I need to make a call
in to PETA's own Linda McCartney

559
00:27:59.887 --> 00:28:04.517
and alert her to the inhumane
living conditions at Rainier West High?

560
00:28:04.600 --> 00:28:06.727
Also. if it dies. it'll smell really bad.

561
00:28:06.811 --> 00:28:10.439
[groaning]

562
00:28:11.440 --> 00:28:13.442
[sighs]

563
00:28:14.568 --> 00:28:15.903
[picks up phone]

564
00:28:15.986 --> 00:28:17.530
[dialing]

565
00:28:19.865 --> 00:28:21.784
Hey. Frank. it's Shane.

566
00:28:21.867 --> 00:28:22.952
[chuckles] Yeah.

567
00:28:23.035 --> 00:28:27.206
Uh. eh-- would you mind bringing
a ladder up to the library?

568
00:28:27.289 --> 00:28:29.208
Oh. and a jar of peanut butter.

569
00:28:31.419 --> 00:28:33.421
For the rat. not for me.

570
00:28:38.968 --> 00:28:40.386
[Frank] Busy day.

571
00:28:40.469 --> 00:28:42.304
I noticed that. too.

572
00:28:42.388 --> 00:28:43.722
[grunts softly]

573
00:28:43.806 --> 00:28:45.724
[intriguing music playing]

574
00:28:45.808 --> 00:28:48.436
[chittering and scurrying]

575
00:28:48.519 --> 00:28:51.105
It sounds like he's right up here. Frank.

576
00:28:52.731 --> 00:28:54.191
[Frank] Give me that peanut butter.

577
00:28:54.275 --> 00:28:55.693
[Anderson grunts. sighs]

578
00:29:04.785 --> 00:29:06.203
[sighs]

579
00:29:08.372 --> 00:29:10.541
-[Frank] Spot me.
-Oh. Yeah.

580
00:29:11.584 --> 00:29:12.918
♪ ♪

581
00:29:13.002 --> 00:29:15.004
[metal creaking]

582
00:29:32.938 --> 00:29:34.940
[upbeat music playing]

583
00:29:38.235 --> 00:29:40.070
-[Frank] Gotcha!
-[gasps]

584
00:29:41.989 --> 00:29:43.365
[chittering]

585
00:29:43.449 --> 00:29:44.825
Giant freakin' rat.

586
00:29:45.951 --> 00:29:47.953
[Anderson] That is no rat.

587
00:29:48.746 --> 00:29:50.206
That is a ferret.

588
00:29:50.998 --> 00:29:52.333
Okay. take it.

589
00:29:54.460 --> 00:29:56.086
I am not touching that.

590
00:29:57.755 --> 00:30:00.299
Kyle? How many times
do we need to tell you?

591
00:30:00.382 --> 00:30:02.092
No ferrets in school.

592
00:30:02.176 --> 00:30:03.594
Get up here.

593
00:30:08.057 --> 00:30:10.976
Uh. would you mind telling us
how that thing got in the vents?

594
00:30:11.060 --> 00:30:12.144
Uh...

595
00:30:12.228 --> 00:30:14.230
Yeah. I must have dozed off. sir.

596
00:30:14.313 --> 00:30:15.731
I have six brothers and three sisters.

597
00:30:15.814 --> 00:30:17.024
Uh-huh.

598
00:30:17.107 --> 00:30:18.776
And this is the only place
I really get any sleep.

599
00:30:18.859 --> 00:30:23.322
Okay. Well. then. you'll be happy to know
you're due back here next Saturday.

600
00:30:23.405 --> 00:30:24.740
Alone.

601
00:30:25.741 --> 00:30:27.868
Uh. thank you very much. sir.

602
00:30:37.086 --> 00:30:39.421
[clearing throat]

603
00:30:39.505 --> 00:30:40.673
[softly] Excuse me. Uh...

604
00:30:40.756 --> 00:30:42.091
[clears throat]

605
00:30:42.174 --> 00:30:43.551
Uh. Principal Anderson?

606
00:30:43.634 --> 00:30:45.219
I think Kimberly's trying
to get your attention.

607
00:30:45.302 --> 00:30:47.429
-[Kimberly clearing throat]
-What is it?

608
00:30:47.513 --> 00:30:49.473
[choking]

609
00:30:49.557 --> 00:30:51.141
[dark music playing]

610
00:30:54.186 --> 00:30:55.354
[Elle] Oh. my God.

611
00:30:55.437 --> 00:30:57.940
Kimberly. do you have a peanut allergy?

612
00:30:58.023 --> 00:30:59.358
[Kimberly clearing throat]

613
00:30:59.441 --> 00:31:00.859
Whoa. whoa. aren't those fatal?

614
00:31:00.943 --> 00:31:02.444
[Liz] Did you bring your EpiPen?

615
00:31:02.528 --> 00:31:04.363
[Elle] You know.
you should really make a habit

616
00:31:04.446 --> 00:31:06.699
of keeping an unexpired pen
on your person at all times

617
00:31:06.782 --> 00:31:08.617
in the event of an anaphylactic emergency.

618
00:31:08.701 --> 00:31:11.579
Well. maybe if she doesn't die right now.
she'll bear that in mind.

619
00:31:11.662 --> 00:31:13.122
Uh. no. there is one.

620
00:31:13.205 --> 00:31:14.873
It's in. uh. the nurse's office.

621
00:31:14.957 --> 00:31:17.167
Um... Uh. keep her calm.

622
00:31:17.251 --> 00:31:19.920
Uh. and if any of you
step foot outside this room.

623
00:31:20.004 --> 00:31:21.964
you will be expelled.

624
00:31:22.548 --> 00:31:24.091
[Kimberly gasping]

625
00:31:24.174 --> 00:31:26.260
[coughs]

626
00:31:28.304 --> 00:31:30.222
[sighs] God. I'm good.

627
00:31:30.306 --> 00:31:31.682
[softly] Jesus Christ.

628
00:31:31.765 --> 00:31:33.392
-[groans]
-[chuckles]

629
00:31:33.475 --> 00:31:34.602
Told you she'd be useful.

630
00:31:34.685 --> 00:31:37.605
[Dustin] Okay. let's do this.
Anderson's old.

631
00:31:37.688 --> 00:31:39.565
I give him four minutes
to get the pen. tops.

632
00:31:40.149 --> 00:31:41.275
That gives me three.

633
00:31:41.358 --> 00:31:42.943
Yeah. are we sure
we want to do this. guys?

634
00:31:43.027 --> 00:31:44.153
He said we could be expelled.

635
00:31:44.236 --> 00:31:45.487
Well. if anyone's gonna do this quickly.

636
00:31:45.571 --> 00:31:47.781
it's gonna be the fastest runner
at this school.

637
00:31:51.660 --> 00:31:53.370
It's me. I'm-I'm the fastest runner.

638
00:31:53.454 --> 00:31:55.080
-[others] We know!
-Okay. Okay.

639
00:31:55.164 --> 00:31:56.582
I'll see you at 11:21. Bye.

640
00:31:56.665 --> 00:31:59.001
[suspenseful music playing]

641
00:32:00.085 --> 00:32:02.087
[panting]

642
00:32:10.679 --> 00:32:12.723
For a second there.
I thought you were in real danger.

643
00:32:12.806 --> 00:32:15.267
Have you considered
pursuing the theatrical arts?

644
00:32:15.351 --> 00:32:17.478
Should someone be standing lookout?

645
00:32:20.606 --> 00:32:22.691
[tense music playing]

646
00:32:22.775 --> 00:32:24.193
[shoe squeaks]

647
00:32:24.276 --> 00:32:26.403
[groaning]

648
00:32:26.487 --> 00:32:27.821
[moans]

649
00:32:27.905 --> 00:32:30.282
♪ ♪

650
00:32:30.366 --> 00:32:31.825
[grunting]

651
00:32:34.411 --> 00:32:36.413
My old neighbor discovered
the Culkin family at a diner.

652
00:32:36.497 --> 00:32:38.666
If you want to put yourself on tape.
I could send it to her.

653
00:32:38.749 --> 00:32:41.418
[scoffs] Um. acting's not really my thing.

654
00:32:41.502 --> 00:32:43.170
[stifled laugh]

655
00:32:43.253 --> 00:32:44.880
[Liz coughs]

656
00:32:46.507 --> 00:32:47.508
Is that funny?

657
00:32:48.384 --> 00:32:51.011
[smacks lips] Kind of. yeah. considering.

658
00:32:51.095 --> 00:32:52.221
Oh. really?

659
00:32:52.304 --> 00:32:54.765
Considering what?

660
00:32:55.933 --> 00:32:58.310
Oh. do you really need me to spell it out?

661
00:32:58.394 --> 00:33:00.854
-Whatever.
-I might benefit

662
00:33:00.938 --> 00:33:03.148
from some spelling out.

663
00:33:03.232 --> 00:33:04.191
[sighs]

664
00:33:04.274 --> 00:33:06.276
[suspenseful music playing]

665
00:33:08.570 --> 00:33:10.823
[panting] Okay. Okay. Okay.

666
00:33:10.906 --> 00:33:12.116
Uh...

667
00:33:14.118 --> 00:33:16.495
[panting]

668
00:33:16.578 --> 00:33:17.663
Okay.

669
00:33:17.746 --> 00:33:18.956
[whispers] Receipts. receipts. receipts.

670
00:33:19.039 --> 00:33:20.332
[Liz] Kimberly's good at acting

671
00:33:20.416 --> 00:33:22.960
because she's in a perpetual state
of performance.

672
00:33:23.043 --> 00:33:25.671
[chuckles] Okay. say what you want.

673
00:33:25.754 --> 00:33:28.716
-I know who I am.
-Great. I know who you are. too.

674
00:33:28.799 --> 00:33:29.842
Great. then we have something in common.

675
00:33:29.925 --> 00:33:32.177
You mean besides the fact
you both have a thing for each other?

676
00:33:33.387 --> 00:33:35.931
♪ ♪

677
00:33:36.014 --> 00:33:38.016
[grunts]

678
00:33:38.100 --> 00:33:40.018
Okay. okay.

679
00:33:40.102 --> 00:33:43.772
Come on. Shane. Come on. Shane.

680
00:33:43.856 --> 00:33:45.774
EpiPen. EpiPen.

681
00:33:45.858 --> 00:33:48.861
Epi... Pen.

682
00:33:48.944 --> 00:33:50.946
[Elle] This book you were
fighting about earlier...

683
00:33:51.029 --> 00:33:54.324
features two ladies looking very wistful.

684
00:33:54.408 --> 00:33:56.368
Like. full of wist.

685
00:33:57.453 --> 00:33:58.996
You were making fun of Liz for reading it.

686
00:33:59.079 --> 00:34:01.790
but I-I looked inside. and you had
checked it out from the library yourself.

687
00:34:01.874 --> 00:34:03.083
Multiple times.

688
00:34:04.543 --> 00:34:07.546
And then you have that secret drawer
full of secret things.

689
00:34:07.629 --> 00:34:09.298
Okay. [sighs]

690
00:34:09.381 --> 00:34:10.883
All right.

691
00:34:10.966 --> 00:34:12.092
Okay.

692
00:34:12.176 --> 00:34:14.178
[muttering]

693
00:34:19.725 --> 00:34:21.143
-[camera clicks]
-[thumb wheel turns]

694
00:34:22.936 --> 00:34:24.104
-[camera clicks]
-[Liz] What secret things?

695
00:34:24.188 --> 00:34:25.773
Your zines.

696
00:34:25.856 --> 00:34:27.399
And also. that camp bracelet.

697
00:34:27.483 --> 00:34:28.650
You went through my stuff?

698
00:34:28.734 --> 00:34:29.985
Not on purpose.

699
00:34:30.068 --> 00:34:33.655
But I think something happened
between you two at that camp--

700
00:34:33.739 --> 00:34:36.950
like. romantically-- and now you're caught
in this whole Sam and Diane thing.

701
00:34:39.286 --> 00:34:40.746
From Cheers.

702
00:34:42.289 --> 00:34:44.625
-[door closes]
-[footsteps approaching]

703
00:34:46.084 --> 00:34:47.878
-[gasps softly]
-[Anderson groans]

704
00:34:47.961 --> 00:34:50.130
You don't hate each other.

705
00:34:50.214 --> 00:34:52.591
You like each other. It's so cute.

706
00:34:57.513 --> 00:35:00.516
-That's... No. That's not. uh. at all...
-I-I don't know...

707
00:35:00.599 --> 00:35:02.476
-where you're going with this one.
-...what is going on there.

708
00:35:02.559 --> 00:35:03.977
Oh. my God.

709
00:35:05.187 --> 00:35:06.980
I did it again. didn't I?

710
00:35:07.064 --> 00:35:08.899
I don't know why my gaydar is so off.

711
00:35:08.982 --> 00:35:12.653
I mean. hearing myself say it.
the camp thing did sound like a stretch.

712
00:35:14.196 --> 00:35:15.864
[door opens]

713
00:35:15.948 --> 00:35:17.825
-[gasps]
-Anderson's on his way.

714
00:35:17.908 --> 00:35:19.952
[♪ Pearl Jam plays "Go"]

715
00:35:20.035 --> 00:35:21.662
Wha-- Miles should be back by now.

716
00:35:25.999 --> 00:35:27.793
And one...

717
00:35:27.876 --> 00:35:29.378
-[camera clicks]
-[thumb wheel turns]

718
00:35:30.379 --> 00:35:31.380
-[camera clicks]
-[thumb wheel turns]

719
00:35:33.549 --> 00:35:35.175
[sighs] Okay.

720
00:35:36.134 --> 00:35:37.636
Guys. we need to do something.

721
00:35:43.725 --> 00:35:45.227
Oh. come on. Miles.

722
00:35:45.310 --> 00:35:46.520
Okay. what do we do?

723
00:35:47.604 --> 00:35:49.022
Um...

724
00:35:53.193 --> 00:35:55.195
♪ ♪

725
00:35:56.572 --> 00:35:58.574
[panting]

726
00:36:00.993 --> 00:36:02.327
Come on.

727
00:36:02.411 --> 00:36:03.954
♪ Oh. please don't go out on me ♪

728
00:36:04.037 --> 00:36:05.664
♪ Don't go on me now ♪

729
00:36:05.747 --> 00:36:08.125
♪ Never acted up before.
don't go on me now...

730
00:36:08.208 --> 00:36:10.627
Uh. uh. quick question:
What are you doing?

731
00:36:11.378 --> 00:36:13.130
[Elle] Anderson won't notice
Miles is missing

732
00:36:13.213 --> 00:36:15.299
if we're all missing.

733
00:36:15.382 --> 00:36:16.884
♪ Just passing it on ♪

734
00:36:16.967 --> 00:36:18.385
♪ Go ♪

735
00:36:20.596 --> 00:36:22.014
♪ Fuck ♪

736
00:36:23.015 --> 00:36:26.101
♪ Once fastened. servile.
now you're getting sharp ♪

737
00:36:26.184 --> 00:36:28.312
-What's this?
-♪ Moving oh so swiftly ♪

738
00:36:28.395 --> 00:36:29.771
♪ with such disarm ♪

739
00:36:29.855 --> 00:36:31.315
♪ I pulled the covers over him ♪

740
00:36:31.398 --> 00:36:33.609
♪ Should've pulled the alarm ♪

741
00:36:33.692 --> 00:36:35.319
-♪ Turned to my nemesis ♪
-[alarm ringing]

742
00:36:35.402 --> 00:36:37.779
♪ a fool. not a fucking god ♪

743
00:36:37.863 --> 00:36:39.406
♪ No...

744
00:36:39.489 --> 00:36:41.575
[alarm continues ringing]

745
00:36:41.658 --> 00:36:43.035
No.

746
00:36:44.703 --> 00:36:46.997
I can't believe you just did that.

747
00:36:47.080 --> 00:36:49.041
It's just a fire alarm.
It'll go off in a second.

748
00:36:49.124 --> 00:36:51.001
so let's get out of... [gasps]

749
00:36:52.794 --> 00:36:53.879
Oh. boy.

750
00:36:55.589 --> 00:36:58.842
♪ Don't go on me ♪♪

751
00:36:58.926 --> 00:37:00.928
♪ ♪

752
00:37:05.891 --> 00:37:06.892
[thumb wheel turns]

753
00:37:10.103 --> 00:37:11.104
[thumb wheel turns]

754
00:37:18.612 --> 00:37:21.365
[Anderson] The sprinklers
didn't just go off. did they?

755
00:37:21.448 --> 00:37:22.699
Huh?

756
00:37:22.783 --> 00:37:25.452
They were triggered by one of you.

757
00:37:26.745 --> 00:37:29.665
Isn't that right. Dustin?

758
00:37:30.999 --> 00:37:34.628
Yeah. You want me to believe this doesn't
fit right in on your rap sheet?

759
00:37:34.711 --> 00:37:37.839
Mascot vandalism.
assembly without permission.

760
00:37:37.923 --> 00:37:40.467
flagrant and recurring skateboarding
in the hallways.

761
00:37:40.550 --> 00:37:43.887
and now turning the entire school
into your own personal swimming pool.

762
00:37:43.971 --> 00:37:45.889
[stifled laugh]

763
00:37:45.973 --> 00:37:47.307
-[wry chuckle] Yeah.
-I'm s... I'm sorry. I'm sorry.

764
00:37:47.391 --> 00:37:49.685
This is all some big joke
to you. huh? Right?

765
00:37:49.768 --> 00:37:52.104
-It's not not funny.
-Okay. All right.

766
00:37:52.187 --> 00:37:53.271
Here's the deal. guys.

767
00:37:53.355 --> 00:37:54.815
[whistles] Okay?

768
00:37:54.898 --> 00:37:58.318
Nobody wants to tell me who did this.
we all come back here next Saturday.

769
00:37:58.402 --> 00:38:00.487
play this game all over again. huh?

770
00:38:00.570 --> 00:38:01.822
Would you like that?

771
00:38:01.905 --> 00:38:03.407
How's that sitting with you. Miles?

772
00:38:04.825 --> 00:38:06.827
Wait a second. isn't that Notre Dame scout

773
00:38:06.910 --> 00:38:09.037
coming to your cross-country meet
next week?

774
00:38:09.121 --> 00:38:11.498
You sure you want to miss that?

775
00:38:11.581 --> 00:38:12.874
Hmm?

776
00:38:13.959 --> 00:38:15.419
Okay. Liz.

777
00:38:15.502 --> 00:38:18.380
You gonna miss another shift
at Bad Vibrations.

778
00:38:18.463 --> 00:38:20.048
while your mom works three jobs?

779
00:38:20.132 --> 00:38:21.591
That seems fair. huh?

780
00:38:21.675 --> 00:38:23.260
And you're on such thin ice already.

781
00:38:26.471 --> 00:38:28.348
Glad you pulled through. Kimberly.

782
00:38:28.432 --> 00:38:29.933
[Kimberly] Yeah.
I'm just relieved I was able

783
00:38:30.017 --> 00:38:33.061
to find that spare pen
hidden in my inside backpack pocket.

784
00:38:33.145 --> 00:38:34.354
Oh. yeah.

785
00:38:34.438 --> 00:38:36.898
I mean. you're not even friends
with these people.

786
00:38:36.982 --> 00:38:40.152
and now you're willing
to take the fall for them?

787
00:38:40.235 --> 00:38:41.987
Huh?

788
00:38:42.070 --> 00:38:45.115
Oh. I guess your parents won't be bragging
about you at church tomorrow.

789
00:38:47.159 --> 00:38:48.994
And finally...

790
00:38:49.995 --> 00:38:51.538
...Miss Woods.

791
00:38:53.331 --> 00:38:55.042
Aren't you above all this?

792
00:38:55.542 --> 00:38:58.378
You weren't even supposed to be here.

793
00:38:58.462 --> 00:39:01.089
And now you're gonna let
some delinquent loser

794
00:39:01.173 --> 00:39:04.509
add "destruction of school property"
to a flawless high school transcript!

795
00:39:04.593 --> 00:39:06.511
Dustin's not a delinquent loser.

796
00:39:06.595 --> 00:39:09.973
Okay. well. remember that next Saturday
when you're sitting next to him.

797
00:39:11.266 --> 00:39:13.310
I actually won't be sitting next to him.

798
00:39:13.393 --> 00:39:15.187
Then start pointing fingers.

799
00:39:18.523 --> 00:39:20.317
Because it was me.

800
00:39:21.401 --> 00:39:23.612
-No. it wasn't.
-It was.

801
00:39:23.695 --> 00:39:26.865
I did this.
and I'm willing to serve my time.

802
00:39:26.948 --> 00:39:28.867
This isn't the Elle Woods I know.

803
00:39:28.950 --> 00:39:31.244
Actually. Principal Anderson.

804
00:39:31.328 --> 00:39:35.749
a "good intention turned unexpected mess"
is the Elle Woods I know.

805
00:39:35.832 --> 00:39:38.794
and I've never felt
more accountable in my life.

806
00:39:40.837 --> 00:39:41.880
Suit yourself.

807
00:39:41.963 --> 00:39:45.383
And. apparently. I can't have you
serve detention in standing water.

808
00:39:45.467 --> 00:39:46.968
so I'm gonna have to call it for today.

809
00:39:47.052 --> 00:39:50.138
But I will see you next weekend.

810
00:39:52.933 --> 00:39:55.393
Maybe you are that kind of girl.

811
00:39:55.477 --> 00:39:57.729
[♪ Simple Minds sings
"Don't You (Forget About Me)"]

812
00:39:57.813 --> 00:40:00.899
♪ Hey. hey. hey. hey ♪

813
00:40:01.900 --> 00:40:05.320
♪ Ooh. ooh ♪

814
00:40:05.403 --> 00:40:08.031
♪ Whoa...

815
00:40:12.828 --> 00:40:17.374
And in conclusion.
that is why a second Saturday of detention

816
00:40:17.457 --> 00:40:20.127
is ultimately a net positive.

817
00:40:20.210 --> 00:40:23.255
While we have not confirmed
the existence of the stolen funds.

818
00:40:23.338 --> 00:40:26.758
we do believe. once we find a discrepancy
in Anderson's paper trail.

819
00:40:26.842 --> 00:40:29.636
we will have the proof we need
to expose his fraud.

820
00:40:29.719 --> 00:40:31.638
And where is this paper trail?

821
00:40:32.556 --> 00:40:34.391
-Developing at Walgreens.
-Okay.

822
00:40:34.474 --> 00:40:38.103
Elle. I didn't love
when you got detention in the first place.

823
00:40:38.186 --> 00:40:42.941
but you started a fire
and flooded your entire campus.

824
00:40:45.026 --> 00:40:48.238
I've started researching
teen wilderness programs.

825
00:40:48.321 --> 00:40:50.031
I couldn't let Miles get expelled.

826
00:40:50.115 --> 00:40:52.868
And maybe there are other sides to me.

827
00:40:52.951 --> 00:40:56.371
Maybe I'm not the rule-abiding Gemini
I always thought.

828
00:40:56.454 --> 00:40:57.747
-[sighs]
-I mean. even Ms. Burke accused me

829
00:40:57.831 --> 00:40:58.999
of being a Cancer.

830
00:40:59.082 --> 00:41:01.626
I hope this isn't your cusp
starting to present.

831
00:41:01.710 --> 00:41:04.337
Okay. what is this cusp thing?

832
00:41:04.421 --> 00:41:06.214
How you were born
during a transitional sun.

833
00:41:06.298 --> 00:41:10.886
how you're a Gemini.
but you're a little bit Cancer. too.

834
00:41:11.887 --> 00:41:13.722
Ms. Burke was right?

835
00:41:13.805 --> 00:41:16.266
But you've always said I was a Gemini.

836
00:41:16.349 --> 00:41:19.644
June 20th. 11:59 p.m.
It's on my birth certificate.

837
00:41:19.728 --> 00:41:22.230
I could've sworn I told you about this.

838
00:41:23.607 --> 00:41:24.941
Told me about what?

839
00:41:25.025 --> 00:41:27.819
How when I was pregnant.
your dad had a pool at the office

840
00:41:27.903 --> 00:41:30.947
and everybody bet
on which day you'd be born.

841
00:41:31.031 --> 00:41:32.199
Not ringing any bells.

842
00:41:32.282 --> 00:41:33.825
Oh. you remember. So fun.

843
00:41:33.909 --> 00:41:36.536
Um. we wanted to stay in the good graces

844
00:41:36.620 --> 00:41:38.830
of the head
of Cedars' plastic surgery division.

845
00:41:38.914 --> 00:41:41.041
who had placed a bet on June 20th.

846
00:41:41.124 --> 00:41:44.252
Which worked out for him.
because I was born on June 20th.

847
00:41:44.336 --> 00:41:46.004
And for us.

848
00:41:46.087 --> 00:41:47.923
Look at the fabulous life we lead.

849
00:41:48.006 --> 00:41:51.426
We have a favorite bistro in Paris

850
00:41:51.509 --> 00:41:54.679
and a pilot on speed dial.

851
00:41:54.763 --> 00:41:56.640
We use "summer" as a verb.

852
00:41:56.723 --> 00:41:57.807
Mom. when was I born?

853
00:41:57.891 --> 00:41:59.476
-June 21st.
-Mom...

854
00:41:59.559 --> 00:42:01.519
Yeah. but 12:01 a.m.

855
00:42:01.603 --> 00:42:03.647
What is two minutes
in the grand scheme of things?

856
00:42:03.730 --> 00:42:05.440
-My whole identity.
-Okay. technically.

857
00:42:05.523 --> 00:42:07.359
your head was out at 11:59.

858
00:42:07.442 --> 00:42:09.319
Great. Great.

859
00:42:09.402 --> 00:42:11.696
So. my head's a Gemini
and my body's a Cancer.

860
00:42:11.780 --> 00:42:14.574
This changes
my entire emotional narrative.

861
00:42:16.201 --> 00:42:21.081
Did you knowingly corroborate the lie
I've been living the past 16 years?

862
00:42:24.376 --> 00:42:26.127
No?

863
00:42:26.211 --> 00:42:27.587
Uh. Miles on the phone.

864
00:42:27.671 --> 00:42:29.214
Said it's important.

865
00:42:32.884 --> 00:42:35.762
How does a Cancer cusp
even answer the phone?

866
00:42:37.347 --> 00:42:38.556
[Elle] This was with the receipts?

867
00:42:38.640 --> 00:42:39.975
It was shoved in the binder.

868
00:42:40.058 --> 00:42:43.061
The note said. "What a beautiful family."

869
00:42:43.144 --> 00:42:45.939
Well. it did
before the sprinklers washed it off.

870
00:42:46.022 --> 00:42:47.774
Okay. so he had a photo of his family?

871
00:42:47.857 --> 00:42:50.235
-Yeah. but the note is creepy.
-And that's not his wife.

872
00:42:50.318 --> 00:42:52.112
-[Dustin] What?
-His wife has red hair.

873
00:42:52.195 --> 00:42:53.947
And they don't have kids.

874
00:42:55.448 --> 00:42:56.825
I've seen that jacket before.

875
00:42:56.908 --> 00:42:59.119
[gasps] I knew
it didn't belong to his wife.

876
00:42:59.202 --> 00:43:01.121
He was dismissed from a school
in Sunnyside. Washington.

877
00:43:01.204 --> 00:43:02.330
for unknown reasons.

878
00:43:02.414 --> 00:43:04.708
This girl's wearing a shirt
that says Sunnyside.

879
00:43:04.791 --> 00:43:06.835
Seems like she's the unknown reason.

880
00:43:08.086 --> 00:43:10.964
So. we're saying this girl
is his daughter?

881
00:43:11.756 --> 00:43:13.591
[sighs] Wow.

882
00:43:13.675 --> 00:43:16.386
I mean. I thought he was having an affair.

883
00:43:16.469 --> 00:43:19.681
but I never thought
he'd have a whole secret family.

884
00:43:19.764 --> 00:43:22.434
Maybe he was stealing the money
to provide for them.

885
00:43:22.517 --> 00:43:25.478
Yeah. but that still doesn't explain
the note.

886
00:43:25.562 --> 00:43:27.230
[Dustin] Unless the money
isn't for his family.

887
00:43:27.314 --> 00:43:28.523
It's a pretty big secret.

888
00:43:28.606 --> 00:43:30.483
Almost worth stealing
thousands of dollars to cover up.

889
00:43:32.485 --> 00:43:35.447
He was paying someone to keep quiet.

890
00:43:35.530 --> 00:43:36.948
Someone must be blackmailing him.

891
00:43:38.033 --> 00:43:39.951
[bicycle approaching]

892
00:43:41.411 --> 00:43:42.829
[brakes squeak]

893
00:43:42.912 --> 00:43:43.997
[Liz] Guys. I need your help.

894
00:43:44.080 --> 00:43:45.999
[panting] It's my mom.

895
00:43:46.082 --> 00:43:48.084
[suspenseful music playing]

896
00:43:51.338 --> 00:43:52.922
[sighs] Oh. fuck.

897
00:43:54.632 --> 00:43:57.260
[sirens wailing]

898
00:43:57.344 --> 00:43:59.137
-[siren whoops]
-[tires screech]

899
00:43:59.721 --> 00:44:01.097
[Elle] What do they want with your mom?

900
00:44:01.181 --> 00:44:03.308
-She swears she didn't do anything.
-Why were they there?

901
00:44:03.391 --> 00:44:05.352
[officer] This is the police!

902
00:44:05.435 --> 00:44:08.605
Step out of your car with your hands up.

903
00:44:08.688 --> 00:44:09.814
[Liz] They were there to arrest her.

904
00:44:09.898 --> 00:44:11.608
-[Donna] Okay.
-[Liz] Look. thousands of dollars in cash

905
00:44:11.691 --> 00:44:13.109
was reported stolen from school today.

906
00:44:13.193 --> 00:44:14.277
[officer] We got the items.

907
00:44:14.361 --> 00:44:16.905
Look. "Rainier West High."
written all over them.

908
00:44:19.407 --> 00:44:20.658
Those aren't mine.

909
00:44:23.078 --> 00:44:24.537
[Liz] They found it in her car.

910
00:44:25.455 --> 00:44:28.291
What? That's impossible.
Donna would never steal.

911
00:44:30.627 --> 00:44:32.128
Well. she'd never steal that much.

912
00:44:32.212 --> 00:44:33.630
[Miles] That doesn't make any sense.

913
00:44:33.713 --> 00:44:35.548
Donna wasn't even at the school today.

914
00:44:35.632 --> 00:44:37.425
Yes. she was. You remember? She...

915
00:44:37.509 --> 00:44:39.969
she dropped off my lunch.

916
00:44:40.053 --> 00:44:43.890
Okay. but Donna was the one
who told us about the receipts.

917
00:44:43.973 --> 00:44:45.392
And then tried to convince us
not to look for them.

918
00:44:45.475 --> 00:44:46.768
[Miles] Didn't we just realize
that someone

919
00:44:46.851 --> 00:44:48.770
was blackmailing Anderson?

920
00:44:50.063 --> 00:44:52.148
I'm sorry. what are you talking about?

921
00:44:52.232 --> 00:44:56.152
We think Anderson has a secret family
and someone knows about it.

922
00:44:57.237 --> 00:44:58.696
[softly] What?

923
00:45:00.073 --> 00:45:01.491
And you think my mom is blackmailing him?

924
00:45:01.574 --> 00:45:03.034
No. No way.

925
00:45:03.118 --> 00:45:04.619
Donna couldn't have done this.

926
00:45:04.702 --> 00:45:07.122
[♪ Simple Minds sing
"Don't You (Forget About Me)"]

927
00:45:11.543 --> 00:45:13.211
Could she?

928
00:45:16.756 --> 00:45:20.260
♪ I say la. la-la-la-la ♪

929
00:45:20.343 --> 00:45:22.637
♪ la-la-la-la ♪

930
00:45:22.720 --> 00:45:26.599
♪ la-la-la-la-la-la-la-la-la-la ♪

931
00:45:26.683 --> 00:45:30.854
♪ la-la-la-la. la-la-la-la ♪

932
00:45:30.937 --> 00:45:35.275
♪ la-la-la-la-la-la-la-la-la-la ♪

933
00:45:35.358 --> 00:45:39.487
♪ la-la-la-la. la-la-la-la ♪

934
00:45:39.571 --> 00:45:43.199
♪ la-la-la-la-la-la-la-la-la-la ♪

935
00:45:43.283 --> 00:45:46.035
♪ When you walk on by ♪

936
00:45:47.620 --> 00:45:52.041
♪ will you call my name? ♪

937
00:45:52.125 --> 00:45:56.129
♪ As you walk on by ♪

938
00:45:56.212 --> 00:46:00.633
♪ will you call my name? ♪

939
00:46:00.717 --> 00:46:03.219
♪ When you walk away ♪♪

939
